column92: My team and I are in the process of configuring/adopting Modern Requirements (https://www.modernrequirements.com/).  This product offers increasing AI support that will perform such tasks as creating Use Case scenarios and diagrams based on specific criteria we provide.  The sky appears limitless.  The critical success factor, however, is applying our expertise when review AI outputs to ensure they align with our expectations, and are succinct, accurate, and complete.  Humans (so far) are still needed!
column93: We have written specifications that call for the use of Universally Unique Identifiers or UUIDs in eXtended Markup Language (XML) messages/documents.  At present, our specifications indicate that UUIDs "should" be used.  One of my analysts proclaimed that since UUIDs have been in use for a few years, we should mandate them.  One small detail, however, is that we defined "valid" UUIDs as those IDs that begin with a non-digit.  Using Microsoft CoPilot, we discovered: 1) there are multiple UUID versions (we hadn't specified one); 2) the rule of UUIDs beginning with a non-digit is not defined in any of the UUID versions (our "standard" was based on an idiosyncrasy of certain XML parsers); and 3) there is an up-and-coming competing standard, Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier, that we should consider before putting a stake in the ground.  In the end, we decided to keep "should" in our UUID specifications and agreed to study and negotiate what our next steps will be.  Pretty cool.
